            <article class="post-preview">
    <a href="https://darcynorman.net/2023/08/26/on-online-teaching-as-a-text-based-adventure-game/">
        <h2 class="post-title">On Online Teaching as a Text-based Adventure Game</h2>
        
        
        
    </a>

    <p class="post-meta">
        <span class="post-meta">
  
  
  <i class="fas fa-calendar"></i>&nbsp;August 26, 2023
  
  
    &nbsp;|&nbsp;<i class="fas fa-clock"></i>&nbsp;5&nbsp;minutes
  
  
    &nbsp;|&nbsp;<i class="fas fa-book"></i>&nbsp;889&nbsp;words
  
  
  
</span>


    </p>
    <div class="post-entry">
        
        My dissertation explored the connections between the design and analysis of video games and our design and understanding of teaching &amp; learning. Much of that work was shaped by a conversation I had with one of my supervisors:
Figure 1.2: One of the conversations that shaped the direction of this dissertation. AI-generated character portrayal provided by Stable Diffusion.
I&rsquo;d written a bit to explore the comparison between video games and online teaching, to see what it might look like if it was experienced as a Zork-like text-based adventure game.
        <a href="https://darcynorman.net/2023/08/26/on-online-teaching-as-a-text-based-adventure-game/" class="post-read-more">Read More</a>
        
        
        
		
		
			<hr><p><em>Images used in this post:</em></p>
		
		<a href="https://darcynorman.net/2023/08/26/on-online-teaching-as-a-text-based-adventure-game/">
		
				<img src="https://theteachinggame.com/images/online-learning-video-game-comic.jpg" alt="A comic, portraying a conversation between myself and a supervisor, about the nature of online learning becoming like a video game - and wondering if the video game was any goodâ€¦">
		
		</a>
		
    </div>

	
		<div class="blog-categories">
			
